After seeing the sign for shabu shabu, I enthusiastically headed in for their reasonably priced lunch specials.
The cost of the lunch special (sukiyaki only) was between 9.95 for prime or 10.95 for kobe chuck.
Opting for the kobe chuck, we settled in for our little afternoon treat.
Initially, the sukiyaki sauce seemed a little on the thin and salty side, but as the liquid kept getting added, the sauce became more sweet.
There wasn't enough negi (green onion) to have that subtle flavour in the broth.
Because of this, I would say the broth would be only okay.
The quality of the ingredients was good although between the two plates, I got more Japanese mushrooms than the hubby did.
Serving sizes for both the vegetables and meat were very reasonable for the pricing.
I wished they did have a little more tofu but that's my personal taste.
My only complaint is the set up.
I just wished we could adjust our own cooking pot temperature.
I felt bad having the server constantly turning up and down our little hot pots.
Luckily the place wasn't busy but still that could be a problem if it was.
Our drinks were constantly refilled promptly.
Overall, it's not the best sukiyaki I've ever had, but it's not the worst I've had either.
Our meal was very satisfying and affordable.

This was my first shabu shabu experience and I have to say that it way ok. Definitely not bad, but not mind-blowing either.
It seemed like family night when we walked in because there were 3 or 4 other families eating there.
I decided to go with the shabu shabu, while my wife and son went with the sukiyaki.
The 6 oz prime rib-eye ($14.95) dinner was sliced very thin and spread out on a plate.
It came with a plate of vegetables (onions, carrots, mushrooms, lettuce), tofu, and udon noodles.
The shabu shabu pot was filled with a seaweed broth and once it got up to temperature it only took a few seconds to cook the steak.
Accompanying the ingredients are two sauces -- a sesame sauce and a ponzu sauce.
The quality of the meat was good, with plenty of marbling throughout, and the sauces added a nice extra dimension to the flavor of the beef.
My wife wasn't as impressed with her vegetable platter ($8.95).
It was basically all the same veggies that I got -- just two plates of it.
She was expecting a wider variety of veggies.
We also got a side order of chicken ($5.95) for our son.
The sukiyaki pot is a shallow iron pot similar in size and depth to a cheesecake pan.
The food is then cooked in the dish after the soy sauced-based liquid in it heats up.
After trying both the shabu shabu and sukiyaki, I have to admit  prefer the latter.
The "stir-fry" quality of the chicken had much bolder flavors and was much sweeter than the shabu shabu preparation.
The style of cooking makes for a fun, interactive experience and would be good for couples on dates or families with older kids who like asian food.

